Project Description

In this scenario, I serve as a Data Analyst on Bellabeats marketing analytics team, focusing on the companys range of health-focused products for women which includes the Bellabeat App, Leaf wearable tracker, Time smartwatch, Spring smart bottle, and Bellabeat Membership. The companys cofounder and Chief Creative Officer believes that analysing smart device usage data can reveal key consumer behaviour trends and unlock new growth opportunities. My task is to analyse publicly available Fitbit Fitness Tracker data, matching it with one of these Bellabeat products to uncover usage patterns and insights that can inform marketing strategy for the chosen product. Insight uncovered can be extended to other Bellabeat products. This report will be divided into sections corresponding to phaseS of the data analysis life cycle - Ask, Prepare, Process, Analyse, Share, and Act.

1. Ask Phase

T asked SMART question and use structured thinking to clearly establish the project goals, requirements, and the overall scope as follows:

1.1 Main Business Question:-

How do wearable smart device users daily activity and sleep patterns reflect opportunities for Bellabeat to market the Time smartwatch (and other products) more effectively to its target audience (health-conscious women)?

1.2 Business Task Statement:-

Identify key behavioral trends from Fitbit smart device data analysis to provide actionable insights that can guide Bellabeats marketing strategies, enhance user personalization, and support sustainable business growth.

1.3 Business Problem:-

Bellabeat, a growing innovator in womens wellness technology, lacks comprehensive insight into consumer smart device usage. This project addresses that gap by analysing available smart device data to generate actionable insights, supporting more effective marketing strategies and product positioning in the competitive global smart device market.

1.4 Business Value:-

This project will deliver actionable, data-driven recommendations that: (a) Provides Bellabeat executives with data-driven insights into consumer behaviour. (b) Enables Bellabeat executives to tailor marketing campaigns based on user habits and preferences. (c) Supports development of personalized product experiences that increase engagement and retention. (d) Provides evidence-based insights to inform strategic decisions for product positioning and messaging.

1.5 Purpose of the Project:

The purpose of this project is to analyse daily activity, heartrate, sleep and weight behaviour patterns of Fitbit device users to identify consumer trends that can guide Bellabeats marketing strategy for the Time smartwatch.

2. Prepare Phase

This phase of my report will focus on describing the data sources that I will use for this analysis, data reliabilty, data bias, Key performance indicators, visualizations that will be created to communicate findings to stakeholders, and analysis timeline.

2.1 Data Source and Information:-

  1. Data source:- Fitbit Fitness Tracker dataset will be retrieved from Mobius/Kaggle website below as directed by Urska Srsen, the co-founder and Chief Creative Office of Bellabeat company: https://www.kaggle.com/arashnic/fitbit

  2. Accessibility and Licensing:- This dataset can be accessed by anyone given that it is CC0: public domain.

  3. Anonymization:- The data set is anonymized, and no personally identifiable information is included.

  4. Content:- This data set contains 18 tables with information on activity, calories, intensities, heart rate, sleep, and weight, often distributed by days, hours, and minutes from approximately 30 eligible Fitbit users.

  5. Limitations: This dataset has several limitations as i have indicated below. But given that the data is generated by Fitbit, I can argue that it is reliable and is validated from the original source.

  6. Gender: There is no mention of the gender of the individuals who consented to submit their personal information. As such, lacking demographic usage. This is an important limitation for our analysis because Bellabeats products are created for use by women. This limitation can lead to bias within our data because we may be analyzing data on men, which can be significantly different to that of women.

  1. Age: There is also no mention of the age of the participants. This means that it is possible that we may be analyzing data of only a specific age segment of the population, which would not represent the entire population

  2. Out of date: The dataset is also not current because the data was collected in the year 2016.

Remark:- Unfortunately, I struggled to find other datasets on smart health device usage to supplement due to the fact that companies do not usually make this information public. However, I will simulate the gender and age group data from same Fitbit Fitness Tracker dataset to help identify demographic usage trends. So I will complete the analysis with the provided dataset, taking into account its limitations and biases.

2.2 Key Performance Indicators:-

  1. Usage Frequency: Daily/weekly engagement with devices.
  2. Activity Trends: Step counts, calories burned, active minutes.
  3. Sleep Trends: Sleep duration, Sedentary Minutes, bedtime/wake patterns.
  4. Engagement Correlation: How often users interact with their physical devices.

4. Analysis Phase

I have processed, cleaned, and merged all of the data that I will use for this project in the process phase. From this data, I will in this analysis phase create derived variables, calculate summary metrics, analyze and visualize.

4.1 Create Derived Variables

merged_fitbit <- merged_fitbit %>%
  mutate(
    weekday = wday(activity_date, label = TRUE, abbr = TRUE),
    week = floor_date(activity_date, "week"),
    daily_avg_steps = mean(total_steps, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_heartrate = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_calories = mean(calories, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_bmi = mean(bmi, na.rm = TRUE),
    active_days = n_distinct(activity_date),
    sleep_hours = total_minutes_asleep / 60,    
    sleep_efficiency = round((total_minutes_asleep / total_time_in_bed) * 100, 1)) %>%
  drop_na(total_steps, total_minutes_asleep) %>%
  distinct(id, activity_date, .keep_all = TRUE)

4.2 Create Activity Levels According to Daily Average Steps

merged_fitbit <- merged_fitbit %>%
  mutate(activity_level = case_when(
      daily_avg_steps >= 10000 ~ "Highly active",
      daily_avg_steps >= 5000 ~ "Moderately active",
      TRUE ~ "sedentary")
      )

4.3 Create BMI Categories According to Average BMI

merged_fitbit <- merged_fitbit %>%
  mutate(bmi_category = case_when(
      avg_bmi < 18.5 ~ "Underweight",
      avg_bmi >= 18.5 & bmi < 25 ~ "Normal",
      avg_bmi >= 25 & bmi < 30 ~ "Overweight",
      avg_bmi >= 30 ~ "Obese",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_)
      )

4.4 Create Heart Rate Level According to Average Heart Rate

merged_fitbit <- merged_fitbit %>%
  mutate(heart_rate_level = case_when(
      avg_heartrate < 60 ~ "Resting",
      avg_heartrate >= 60 & avg_heartrate < 100 ~ "Normal",
      avg_heartrate >= 100 & avg_heartrate < 140 ~ "Fat Burn",
      avg_heartrate >= 140 ~ "Cardio",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_)
      )

4.5 Add Simulated Gender and Age_group Based on Probability

set.seed(123)
merged_fitbit <- merged_fitbit %>%
  mutate(
    ### Gender: probabilistic assignment
    gender = sample(c("Female", "Male"), n(), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.55, 0.45)),
    ### Age group: probabilistic assignment
    age_group = sample(c("<25","25-34","35-44","45+"), n(), replace = TRUE,
                       prob = c(0.2,0.4,0.25,0.15)))

4.8 Analysis and Visualizations

Lifestyle Rhythm & Weekly Activity Patterns:

Visual Goal: Uncover when users are most or least active, revealing temporal engagement trends.

(a) Weekly Activity Heatmap
P1 <- merged_fitbit %>%
  group_by(activity_date, weekday, week) %>%
  summarise(active_users = n_distinct(id)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = weekday, y = week, fill = active_users)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "A") +
  labs(title = "Weekly Active Users Patterns by Day",
       x = "Day of Week", y = "Week Number", fill = "Active Users") +
  theme_minimal() +

5. Share Phase

5.1 Summary of Findings

This analysis explored Fitbit-derived behavioral data to understand wellness patterns, activity engagement, demographic insights among users, with the aim of uncovering trends that can guide Bellabeats marketing strategy for its Time Smartwatch.

(a) Scope of Work:

Data was cleaned, merged, and enriched with derived metrics including daily average steps, active days, heart rate level, sleep efficiency, BMI category, activity level, and probabilistic gender and age groups. Visualizations were generated to examine patterns across activity, sleep, and health indicators, providing a holistic wellness profile of users.

(b) Key Trends:
Lifestyle Rhythm & Weekly Activity Patterns (Weekly Activity Heatmap)
  • Activity peaks occurred on weekends, with midweek declines suggesting drop-offs in engagement.
  • Highly active users maintained consistent step counts across the week, while sedentary users showed strong variability.
Wellness Balance (Bubble Plot - Sleep vs Steps vs Calories)
  • Users with higher activity levels also showed greater sleep efficiency, suggesting effective recovery behaviors.
  • Average sleep duration ranged between 6.57.5 hours, with moderate correlation to daily activity levels.
Demographic Insights (Faceted Boxplots Activity by Age and Gender)
  • Younger users (1834) displayed higher variability in activity, while older users (45+) showed consistent but moderate activity and better sleep efficiency.
  • Probabilistic female users showed slightly higher sleep efficiency and moderate step levels a key target segment for Bellabeats wellness-focused branding.
Health Segmentation (BMI Composition by Activity Level, Gender, and Age Group)
  • Users classified as Normal BMI dominated the Moderately Active and Highly Active categories.
  • Overweight and Obese segments overlapped with lower daily step averages, revealing potential for targeted coaching.
Engagement Personas Identified (Multi-dimensional Scatter Heart Rate, Steps, Calories, BMI)
  • Performance Enthusiasts: High steps, high heart rate, low sleep hours likely fitness-oriented.
  • Balanced Wellness Users: Moderate activity and optimal sleep align with Bellabeats holistic message.
  • Sedentary Rebounders: Low steps, lower sleep efficiency opportunity for reactivation and motivational campaigns.

6.4 Lessons Learned

  1. Behavior Intent: Users show high variability engagement depends more on motivation cycles than demographics.
  2. Moderate Activity is the Sweet Spot: Users dont want to be athletes; they want balance and achievable progress.
  3. Sleep Data is Underleveraged: Sleep metrics strongly predict wellness perception key to emotional engagement.
  4. Personalization Drives Loyalty: Segmented, persona-based engagement has higher conversion potential than generic campaigns.
  5. Visualization Matters: Presenting clear, empathetic visuals (activity + sleep + heart-rate) creates stronger leadership understanding and buy-in.

6.5 Conclusion

This data-driven analysis has provided Bellabeat with a clear, evidence-backed marketing roadmap for the Time smartwatch. By understanding users lifestyle patterns and emotional motivators, Bellabeat can strengthen its market leadership in womens wellness technology through empathetic, personalized, and data-guided engagement.

Final Thought: The Bellabeat Time smartwatch should not be marketed merely as a wearable, but as a personal wellness companion intelligently attuned to each users rhythm of life.
